<td colspan="2" class="" style="text-align:center; line-height:1.3em; vertical-align:middle;">
<div style="padding-top:0.25em; text-align:left; font-style:90%;"><b>Notes</b><br />
Cambridge did not have PhD degrees until 1919. So Haldane obtained an M.A., but then directly worked under <a href="/wiki/Frederick_Gowland_Hopkins" title="Frederick Gowland Hopkins">Hopkins</a> who was the equivalent of a doctoral mentor.</div>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><b>John Burdon Sanderson Haldane</b> <a href="/wiki/Royal_Society#Fellowship" title="Royal Society">FRS</a> (<span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1892-11-05"><a href="/wiki/November_5" title="November 5">5 November</a> <a href="/wiki/1892" title="1892">1892</a></span> – <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1964-12-01"><a href="/wiki/December_1" title="December 1">1 December</a> <a href="/wiki/1964" title="1964">1964</a></span>), known as Jack (but who used 'J.B.S.' in his printed works), was a <a href="/wiki/UK" title="UK" class="mw-redirect">British</a>-born <a href="/wiki/Geneticist" title="Geneticist">geneticist</a> and <a href="/wiki/Evolutionary_biologist" title="Evolutionary biologist" class="mw-redirect">evolutionary biologist</a>. He was one of the founders (along with <a href="/wiki/Ronald_Fisher" title="Ronald Fisher">Ronald Fisher</a> and <a href="/wiki/Sewall_Wright" title="Sewall Wright">Sewall Wright</a>) of <a href="/wiki/Population_genetics" title="Population genetics">population genetics</a>.</p>
